      ],
      "uuid": "190b088f-7048-4a4d-b736-5e60bb4e888d"
    },
    {
      "start_time": 348,
      "end_time": 357,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "So, recently I was in one of John Lilly's isolation tanks and I thought, what a perfect time to do this thing I've always been afraid to do."
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        {
          "tag": "Speaking",
          "category": "Voice"
        },
        {
          "tag": "Transcription",
          "category": "Type"
        },
        {
          "category": "Speaker",
          "tag": "Michael McClure"
        }
      ],
      "uuid": "294ba7a1-e404-4871-a104-39c675552860"
    },
    {
      "start_time": 357,
      "end_time": 358,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "The audience laughs."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "\n\n"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        {
          "category": "Voice",
          "tag": "Situational"
        },
        {
          "tag": "Notes",
          "category": "Type"
        },
        {
          "category": "Speaker",
          "tag": "Audience"
        }
      ],
      "uuid": "ea69d165-b18e-4af0-9577-2b7639afba62"
    },
    {
      "start_time": 358,
      "end_time": 363,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "What difference would it make here? So I did, and I did know it by heart, but I think I'll read it here anyway."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "\n\n"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        {
          "tag": "Speaking",
          "category": "Voice"
        },
        {
          "tag": "Transcription",
          "category": "Type"
        },
        {
          "category": "Speaker",
          "tag": "Michael McClure"
        }
      ],
      "uuid": "37f3b68b-8445-4d21-b7ce-329432067cc6"
    },
    {
      "start_time": 363,
      "end_time": 363,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "The reference to John Lilly, the neurophysicist-turned-cetologist-cum-“cosmonaut of heightened consciousness,” is curiously overdetermined (Burnett 14). Emerging from the same incipient “culture of feedback” that would come to characterize ecological thought in the 1970s, McClure’s beast language parallels, in an eccentric key, the experimental work Lilly had begun in the late 1950s on the intelligence of bottlenose dolphins and possibilities for interspecies communication, as documented in "
            },
            {
              "text": "Man and Dolphin",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " (1961) and "
            },
            {
              "text": "The Mind of the Dolphin",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " (1967) (see Belgrad 138-73). And yet at the same time that he was researching dolphins, Lilly was also responsible for major contributions to the field of sensory-deprivation research, including the invention of the water-immersion isolation tank. Lilly’s "
            },
            {
              "text": "The Deep Self: Profound Relaxation and the Tank Isolation Technique",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " (1977) was published the year after McClure’s reading. It includes the logs of “scores of men and women volunteers,” from Gregory Bateson to Burgess Meredith, “who have recorded their extraordinary experiences” in a Malibu facility with five isolation tanks. Though McClure is not featured in the book, it seems likely he made the trek, and this presumption entails an irony worth pausing over. For Lilly, the isolated flotation tank is a therapeutic means of probing interior experience by cleaving mind from body: “For a businessperson, a scientist, a professional of any sort, this is a boon: to be able to think, free of physical fatigue of the body. The method allows one to become free within a few minutes” (22)."
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "tags": [
        {
          "category": "Voice",
          "tag": "Situational"
        },
        {
          "tag": "Notes",
